i>wīg</i> ‘battle’). The name may sometimes have been confused with   Selwyn  .","Americanized form of French   Salois  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Selway","meanings":["English (Somerset and Devon): variant of   Salway  ."]},{"name":"Soloway","meanings":["English: variant of   Salway  .","Americanized form of Jewish, Ukrainian, or Belorussian   Solovey   ‘nightingale’."]},{"name":"Selwyn","meanings":["English (Gloucestershire):","from the Middle English personal name <i>Selewin(e)</i> (Old English <i>Selewine</i>, perhaps from <i>sele</i> ‘hall’ or <i>sǣl</i> ‘happiness, prosperity’ + <i>wine</i> ‘friend’).","of Norman origin, perhaps from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Selvein</i>, <i>Silvein</i> (from Latin <i>Silvanus</i>, an adjective from <i>silva</i> ‘woodland’), with vocalization of /v/ to /w/, possibly through influence of the name above. In Anglo-Norman usage both <i>Selvein</i> and <i>Silvester</i> were sometimes Latinized as <i>Salvagius</i> ‘wild, savage’ (see   Sylvester   and   Savage  ), though whether the vernacular surnames were ever interchangeable is a question for further research."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":29,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":60,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Saleway was born in 1230, in Norton Bridge, Staffordshire, England, his father, Geoffery Saleway, was 30 and his mother, Saleway, was 20. He had at least 2 sons with Saleway. He died in 1300, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1230–1300":"1230–1300","1250–1310":"1250–1310","1270–1307":"1270–1307","1272–1307":"1272–1307","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1210–1280":"1210–1280","1259":"1259","1300":"1300","1200":"1200","1310":"1310","1210":"1210","1230":"1230","1272":"1272","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1307":"1307","1290":"1290","Norton Bridge, Staffordshire, England":"Norton Bridge, Staffordshire, England","England":"England","Cannock, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cannock, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1230–1300":"1230–1300","1250–1310":"1250–1310","1270–1307":"1270–1307","1272–1307":"1272–1307","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1210–1280":"1210–1280","1259":"1259","1300":"1300","1200":"1200","1310":"1310","1210":"1210","1230":"1230","1272":"1272","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1307":"1307","1290":"1290","Norton Bridge, Staffordshire, England":"Norton Bridge, Staffordshire, England","England":"England","Cannock, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cannock, Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1230–1300":"1230–1300","1250–1310":"1250–1310","1270–1307":"1270–1307","1272–1307":"1272–1307","1200–Male":"1200–Décédé","1210–1280":"1210–1280","1259":"1259","1300":"